				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mat=
hematical operation on vectors in 3D space</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the cross product of two vectors in three-dimensional Euclidean s=
pace. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_pr=
oduct_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Cross product (disam=
biguation)">Cross product (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cross_product_vector.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Cross_product_vector.svg/250px-Cross_product_vector.s=
vg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"579" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"548" data-file-height=3D"1270"></a><figcaption>Th=
e cross product with respect to a right-handed coordinate system</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>cross product</b> or <b>vector product</b> (=
occasionally <b>directed area product</b>, to emphasize its geometric signi=
ficance) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_operation" ti=
tle=3D"Binary operation">binary operation</a> on two <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean vector">vectors</a>=
 in a three-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientatio=
n_(vector_space)" title=3D"Orientation (vector space)">oriented</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector_space" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Euclidean vector space">Euclidean vector space</a> (named her=
e <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math =
xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle E}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>E</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle E}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4232c9de2ee3eec0a9c0a19b15ab92daa6223f9b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.776ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle E}"=
></span>), and is denoted by the symbol <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe=
-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml=
-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/=
MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \times }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \times }</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0ffafff1ad26cbe49045f19a67ce532116a32703" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: 0.019ex; margin-bottom: -0.19ex; width:1.808ex; height:1.509ex;" al=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \times }"></span>. Given two <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Linearly_independent_vectors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Linearly independent vectors">linearly independent vectors</a> <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>a</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>b</b></span>, t=
he cross product, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b></span> (=
read "a cross b"), is a vector that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a> to both <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><b>a</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>b</b></sp=
an>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and thus <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_(geometry)" title=3D"Normal (geome=
try)">normal</a> to the plane containing them. It has many applications in =
mathematics, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Phy=
sics">physics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" ti=
tle=3D"Engineering">engineering</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Computer_programming" title=3D"Computer programming">computer progra=
mming</a>. It should not be confused with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Dot_product" title=3D"Dot product">dot product</a> (projection =
product).
</p><p>The magnitude of the cross product equals the area of a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">paralle=
logram</a> with the vectors for sides; in particular, the magnitude of the =
product of two perpendicular vectors is the product of their lengths. The <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" title=3D"Unit =
of measurement">units</a> of the cross-product are the product of the units=
 of each vector. If two vectors are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Parallel_vectors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Parallel vectors">parall=
el</a> or are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiparallel_vectors=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Antiparallel vectors">anti-parallel</a> (t=
hat is, they are linearly dependent), or if either one has zero length, the=
n their cross product is zero.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_2-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-:2-2"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>The cross product is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antico=
mmutativity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anticommutativity">anticommutat=
ive</a> (that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b> =3D =E2=
=88=92 <b>b</b> =C3=97 <b>a</b></span>) and is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Distributivity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Distributivity"=
>distributive</a> over addition, that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>a</b> =
=C3=97 (<b>b</b> + <b>c</b>) =3D <b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b> + <b>a</b> =C3=97=
 <b>c</b></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
 space <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 E}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>E</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle E}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/4232c9de2ee3eec0a9c0a19b15ab92daa6223f9b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.776ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle E}"=
></span> together with the cross product is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Algebra_over_a_field" title=3D"Algebra over a field">algebra o=
ver the real numbers</a>, which is neither <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Commutative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Commutative">commutati=
ve</a> nor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Associative">associative</a>, but is a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_algebra" title=3D"Lie algebra">Lie algebra</a=
> with the cross product being the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Lie_bracket" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lie bracket">Lie bracket</a>.
</p><p>Like the dot product, it depends on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Metric_space" title=3D"Metric space">metric</a> of the space u=
nder consideration, but unlike the dot product, it also depends on a choice=
 of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientation_(mathematics)" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orientation (mathematics)">orientation</a> o=
f the space (this is why the space must be oriented). The cross product is =
invariant under a rotation of the basis but is changed into its opposite by=
 an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odd_permutation" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Odd permutation">odd permutation</a> of the basis vectors=
. Therefore, the cross product is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Pseudovector" title=3D"Pseudovector">pseudovector</a>.
</p><p>In connection with the cross product, the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Exterior_algebra" title=3D"Exterior algebra">exterior produc=
t</a> of vectors can be used in arbitrary dimensions (with a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bivector" title=3D"Bivector">bivector</a> or <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2-form" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"2-form">2-form</a> result) and is independent of the orientation of the=
 space.
</p><p>The product can be generalized in various ways, using the orientatio=
n and metric structure just as for the traditional 3-dimensional cross prod=
uct; one can, in <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
n</span> dimensions, take the product of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =
=E2=88=92 1</span> vectors to produce a vector perpendicular to all of them=
. But if the product is limited to non-trivial binary products with vector =
results, it exists only in three and seven dimensions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-M=
assey2_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cr=
oss_product#cite_note-Massey2-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Seven-dimensional_cross_product" title=3D"Seven-dimensional c=
ross product">cross-product in seven dimensions</a> has undesirable propert=
ies (e.g. it <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seven-dimensional_cro=
ss_product#Relation_to_the_octonions" title=3D"Seven-dimensional cross prod=
uct">fails</a> to satisfy the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaco=
bi_identity" title=3D"Jacobi identity">Jacobi identity</a>), so it is not u=
sed in mathematical physics to represent quantities such as multi-dimension=
al <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space-time" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Space-time">space-time</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-4">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> (See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#Gene=
ralizations">=C2=A7&nbsp;Generalizations</a> below for other dimensions.)
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Right_hand_rule_cross_product.svg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/d/d2/Right_hand_rule_cross_product.svg/250px-Right_hand_rule_cros=
s_product.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"226" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"507" data-file-height=3D"459"></a><fig=
caption>Finding the direction of the cross product by the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-hand_rule" title=3D"Right-hand rule">right-ha=
nd rule</a> </figcaption></figure>
<p>The cross product of two vectors <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> is defined only i=
n three-dimensional space and is denoted by <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b>=
 =C3=97 <b>b</b></span>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physic=
s" title=3D"Physics">physics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Applied_mathematics" title=3D"Applied mathematics">applied mathematics</=
a>, the wedge notation <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =E2=88=A7 <b>b</b></=
span> is often used (in conjunction with the name <i>vector product</i>),<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_not=
e-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although in p=
ure mathematics such notation is usually reserved for just the exterior pro=
duct, an abstraction of the vector product to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> dimensions.
</p><p>The cross product <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b></s=
pan> is defined as a vector <b>c</b> that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendicular</a> (orthog=
onal) to both <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>, with a direction given by the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right-hand_rule" title=3D"Right-hand rule=
">right-hand rule</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-:1-1"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 and a magnitude equal to the area of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> that the v=
ectors span.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-:2-2"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The cross product is defined by the formula<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#ci=
te_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cullen_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-Cullen-9"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
