400" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>The cross product <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b></span> (vertical, in purple) changes a=
s the angle between the vectors <b>a</b> (blue) and <b>b</b> (red) changes.=
 The cross product is always orthogonal to both vectors, and has magnitude =
zero when the vectors are parallel and maximum magnitude =E2=80=96<b>a</b>=
=E2=80=96=E2=80=96<b>b</b>=E2=80=96 when they are orthogonal.</figcaption><=
/figure>
<p>The direction of the vector <b>n</b> depends on the chosen orientation o=
f the space. Conventionally, it is given by the right-hand rule, where one =
simply points the forefinger of the right hand in the direction of <b>a</b>=
 and the middle finger in the direction of <b>b</b>. Then, the vector <b>n<=
/b> is coming out of the thumb (see the adjacent picture). Using this rule =
implies that the cross product is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Anticommutativity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anticommutativity">anti-c=
ommutative</a>; that is, <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>b</b> =C3=97 <b>a</b> =
=3D =E2=88=92(<b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b>)</span>. By pointing the forefinger =
toward <b>b</b> first, and then pointing the middle finger toward <b>a</b>,=
 the thumb will be forced in the opposite direction, reversing the sign of =
the product vector.
</p><p>As the cross product operator depends on the orientation of the spac=
e, in general the cross product of two vectors is not a "true" vector, but =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudovector" title=3D"Pseudovec=
tor">pseudovector</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Names_and_origin">Names and=
 origin</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCros=
s_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Names a=
nd origin"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sarrus_rule.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/6/66/Sarrus_rule.svg/330px-Sarrus_rule.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" =
width=3D"310" height=3D"168" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5=
44" data-file-height=3D"295"></a><figcaption>According to <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarrus%27s_rule" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sar=
rus's rule">Sarrus's rule</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">determinant</a> of a 3=C3=973 matrix in=
volves multiplications between matrix elements identified by crossed diagon=
als</figcaption></figure>
<p>In 1842, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Rowan_Hamilton=
" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton">William Rowan Hamilton</a> first describ=
ed the algebra of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion" titl=
e=3D"Quaternion">quaternions</a> and the non-commutative Hamilton product. =
In particular, when the Hamilton product of two vectors (that is, pure quat=
ernions with zero scalar part) is performed, it results in a quaternion wit=
h a scalar and vector part. The scalar and vector part of this Hamilton pro=
duct corresponds to the negative of dot product and cross product of the tw=
o vectors.
</p><p>In 1881, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josiah_Willard_Gib=
bs" title=3D"Josiah Willard Gibbs">Josiah Willard Gibbs</a>,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross=
_product#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and independently <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Heaviside" title=3D"Oliver Heaviside">Oliver He=
aviside</a>, introduced the notation for both the dot product and the cross=
 product using a period (<span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =E2=8B=85 <b>b</b>=
</span>) and an "=C3=97" (<span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b></=
span>), respectively, to denote them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ucd_11-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_not=
e-ucd-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1877, to emphasize the fact that the result of a dot product is a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(mathematics)" title=3D"Sc=
alar (mathematics)">scalar</a> while the result of a cross product is a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean =
vector">vector</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Kingdo=
n_Clifford" title=3D"William Kingdon Clifford">William Kingdon Clifford</a>=
 coined the alternative names <b>scalar product</b> and <b>vector product</=
b> for the two operations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ucd_11-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-ucd-11"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> These alternative names are still widely used in the literature.
</p><p>Both the cross notation (<span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b=
</b></span>) and the name <i>cross product</i> were possibly inspired by th=
e fact that each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_component"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scalar component">scalar component</a> of <=
span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =C3=97 <b>b</b></span> is computed by multip=
lying non-corresponding components of <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. Conversely, a =
dot product <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>a</b> =E2=8B=85 <b>b</b></span> invol=
ves multiplications between corresponding components of <b>a</b> and <b>b</=
b>. As explained <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#Mat=
rix_notation">below</a>, the cross product can be expressed in the form of =
a determinant of a special <span class=3D"nowrap">3 =C3=97 3</span> matrix.=
 According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarrus%27s_rule" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sarrus's rule">Sarrus's rule</a>, this involves=
 multiplications between matrix elements identified by crossed diagonals.
</p>
