<p>This result can be generalized to higher dimensions using <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_algebra" title=3D"Geometric algebra">g=
eometric algebra</a>. In particular in any dimension bivectors can be ident=
ified with skew-symmetric matrices, so the product between a skew-symmetric=
 matrix and vector is equivalent to the grade-1 part of the product of a bi=
vector and vector.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-lounesto2001_19-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-lounesto=
2001-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> In three dimensions bivectors are <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hodge_dual" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hodge dual"=
>dual</a> to vectors so the product is equivalent to the cross product, wit=
h the bivector instead of its vector dual. In higher dimensions the product=
 can still be calculated but bivectors have more degrees of freedom and are=
 not equivalent to vectors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-lounesto2001_19-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note=
-lounesto2001-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This notation is also often much easier to work with, for example, i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epipolar_geometry" title=3D"Epip=
olar geometry">epipolar geometry</a>.
</p><p>From the general properties of the cross product follows immediately=
