</p><p>The second and third equations can be obtained from the first by sim=
ply vertically rotating the subscripts, <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i> =E2=
=86=92 <i>y</i> =E2=86=92 <i>z</i> =E2=86=92 <i>x</i></span>. The problem, =
of course, is how to remember the first equation, and two options are avail=
able for this purpose: either to remember the relevant two diagonals of Sar=
rus's scheme (those containing <i><b>i</b></i>), or to remember the xyzzy s=
equence.
</p><p>Since the first diagonal in Sarrus's scheme is just the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_diagonal" title=3D"Main diagonal">main di=
agonal</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#Ma=
trix_notation">above-mentioned 3=C3=973 matrix</a>, the first three letters=
 of the word xyzzy can be very easily remembered.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cross_visualization">Cross =
