=3Dq_{e}\left(\mathbf {E} +\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} \right)}</annotat=
ion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/799b9238a8f2183426d69bcff68f643a5039af90" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:19.763ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
mathbf {F} =3Dq_{e}\left(\mathbf {E} +\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} \right=
)}"></span>
</p><p>Since velocity <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</=
b></span>,</span> force <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>F</b></span> and electri=
c field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span> are all <i>true</i> vectors=
, the magnetic field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is a <i>pseudo=
vector</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other">Other</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Other"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_calculus" title=3D"Ve=
ctor calculus">vector calculus</a>, the cross product is used to define the=
 formula for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_operator" =
title=3D"Vector operator">vector operator</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Curl_(mathematics)" title=3D"Curl (mathematics)">curl</a>.
</p><p>The trick of rewriting a cross product in terms of a matrix multipli=
cation appears frequently in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epipo=
lar_geometry" title=3D"Epipolar geometry">epipolar</a> and multi-view geome=
try, in particular when deriving matching constraints.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"As_an_external_product">As =
an external product</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DCross_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: As an external product"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Exterior_calc_cross_product.s=
vg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Exterior_calc_cross_product.svg/250px-Exterior=
_calc_cross_product.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"231=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"231" data-file-height=3D"213=
"></a><figcaption>The cross product in relation to the exterior product. In=
 red are the orthogonal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_vecto=
r" title=3D"Unit vector">unit vector</a>, and the "parallel" unit bivector.=
</figcaption></figure>
<p>The cross product can be defined in terms of the exterior product. It ca=
n be generalized to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_produ=
ct#External_product">external product</a> in other than three dimensions.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This generalization allows =
a natural geometric interpretation of the cross product. In <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exterior_algebra" title=3D"Exterior algebra">exte=
rior algebra</a> the exterior product of two vectors is a bivector. A bivec=
tor is an oriented plane element, in much the same way that a vector is an =
oriented line element. Given two vectors <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>, one can vie=
w the bivector <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>b</i></span> as=
 the oriented parallelogram spanned by <i>a</i> and <i>b</i>. The cross pro=
duct is then obtained by taking the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Hodge_star" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hodge star">Hodge star</a> of =
the bivector <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i> =E2=88=A7 <i>b</i></span>, map=
ping <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-vector" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"P-vector">2-vectors</a> to vectors:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle a\times b=3D\star (a\wedge b).}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mo>=E2=8B=86<!-- =E2=8B=86 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=A7<!-- =E2=88=A7 --></mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle a\times b=3D\=
star (a\wedge b).}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e1d5ac0b57cac1a3209637a9195e25a5119a7b34" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:16.595ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle a=
\times b=3D\star (a\wedge b).}"></span>
</p><p>This can be thought of as the oriented multi-dimensional element "pe=
rpendicular" to the bivector. In a <i>d-</i>dimensional space, Hodge star t=
akes a <i>k</i>-vector to a (<i>d=E2=80=93k</i>)-vector; thus only in <i>d =
=3D</i> 3 dimensions is the result an element of dimension one (3=E2=80=932=
 =3D 1), i.e. a vector. For example, in <i>d =3D</i> 4 dimensions, the cros=
s product of two vectors has dimension 4=E2=80=932 =3D 2, giving a bivector=
. Thus, only in three dimensions does cross product define an algebra struc=
ture to multiply vectors.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_=
product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Generali=
zations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>There are several ways to generalize the cross product to higher dimensi=
ons.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Lie_algebra">Lie algebra</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Lie algebra"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_algebra" title=
=3D"Lie algebra">Lie algebra</a></div>
<p>The cross product can be seen as one of the simplest Lie products, and i=
s thus generalized by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_algebra"=
 title=3D"Lie algebra">Lie algebras</a>, which are axiomatized as binary pr=
oducts satisfying the axioms of multilinearity, skew-symmetry, and the Jaco=
bi identity. Many Lie algebras exist, and their study is a major field of m=
athematics, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_theory" tit=
le=3D"Lie theory">Lie theory</a>.
</p><p>For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heisenberg=
_algebra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Heisenberg algebra">Heisenberg alg=
ebra</a> gives another Lie algebra structure on <span class=3D"mwe-math-ele=
ment mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-mat=
h-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/19=
98/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbf {R} ^{3}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
