</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Quaternions">Quaternions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Quaternions"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternions_a=
nd_spatial_rotation" title=3D"Quaternions and spatial rotation">quaternions=
 and spatial rotation</a></div>
<p>The cross product can also be described in terms of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion" title=3D"Quaternion">quaternions</a>.
In general, if a vector <span class=3D"nowrap">[<i>a</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>a<=
/i><sub>2</sub>, <i>a</i><sub>3</sub>]</span> is represented as the quatern=
ion <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>a</i><sub>1</sub><i>i</i> + <i>a</i><sub>2</s=
ub><i>j</i> + <i>a</i><sub>3</sub><i>k</i></span>, the cross product of two=
 vectors can be obtained by taking their product as quaternions and deletin=
g the real part of the result. The real part will be the negative of the do=
t product of the two vectors.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Octonions">Octonions</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section: Octonions"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seven-dimensional_cross_=
product" title=3D"Seven-dimensional cross product">Seven-dimensional cross =
product</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octonion" title=3D=
"Octonion">Octonion</a></div>
<p>A cross product for 7-dimensional vectors can be obtained in the same wa=
y by using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octonion" title=3D"=
Octonion">octonions</a> instead of the quaternions. The nonexistence of non=
trivial vector-valued cross products of two vectors in other dimensions is =
related to the result from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurwitz=
%27s_theorem_(normed_division_algebras)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hur=
witz's theorem (normed division algebras)">Hurwitz's theorem</a> that the o=
nly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normed_division_algebra" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Normed division algebra">normed division algebras=
</a> are the ones with dimension 1, 2, 4, and 8.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Exterior_product">Exterior =
product</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCros=
s_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Exteri=
or product"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exterior_algebra" t=
itle=3D"Exterior algebra">Exterior algebra</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_vector_algebra_and_geometric_algebra#Cross_a=
nd_exterior_products" title=3D"Comparison of vector algebra and geometric a=
lgebra">Comparison of vector algebra and geometric algebra =C2=A7&nbsp;Cros=
s and exterior products</a></div>
<p>In general dimension, there is no direct analogue of the binary cross pr=
oduct that yields specifically a vector. There is however the exterior prod=
uct, which has similar properties, except that the exterior product of two =
vectors is now a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-vector" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P-vector">2-vector</a> instead of an ordinary vec=
tor. As mentioned above, the cross product can be interpreted as the exteri=
or product in three dimensions by using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Hodge_star" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hodge star">Hodge star=
</a> operator to map 2-vectors to vectors. The Hodge dual of the exterior p=
roduct yields an <span class=3D"nowrap">(<i>n</i> =E2=88=92 2)</span>-vecto=
r, which is a natural generalization of the cross product in any number of =
dimensions.
</p><p>The exterior product and dot product can be combined (through summat=
ion) to form the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_algebra=
" title=3D"Geometric algebra">geometric product</a> in geometric algebra.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"External_product">External =
product</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCros=
s_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Extern=
al product"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>As mentioned above, the cross product can be interpreted in three dimens=
ions as the Hodge dual of the exterior product. In any finite <i>n</i> dime=
nsions, the Hodge dual of the exterior product of <span class=3D"nowrap"><i=
>n</i> =E2=88=92 1</span> vectors is a vector. So, instead of a binary oper=
ation, in arbitrary finite dimensions, the cross product is generalized as =
the Hodge dual of the exterior product of some given <span class=3D"nowrap"=
><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1</span> vectors. This generalization is called <b>exte=
rnal product</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Commutator_product">Commuta=
tor product</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Cross_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Co=
mmutator product"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
