pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>The commutator product could be generalised to arbitrary <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivector#Geometric_algebra" title=3D"Multi=
vector">multivectors</a> in three dimensions, which results in a multivecto=
r consisting of only elements of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
raded_vector_space" title=3D"Graded vector space">grades</a> 1 (1-vectors/<=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#Handedness">true vect=
ors</a>) and 2 (2-vectors/pseudovectors). While the commutator product of t=
wo 1-vectors is indeed the same as the exterior product and yields a 2-vect=
or, the commutator of a 1-vector and a 2-vector yields a true vector, corre=
sponding instead to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_=
algebra#Extensions_of_the_inner_and_exterior_products" title=3D"Geometric a=
lgebra">left and right contractions</a> in geometric algebra. The commutato=
r product of two 2-vectors has no corresponding equivalent product, which i=
s why the commutator product is defined in the first place for 2-vectors. F=
urthermore, the commutator triple product of three 2-vectors is the same as=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_triple_product" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vector triple product">vector triple product</a> =
of the same three pseudovectors in vector algebra. However, the commutator =
triple product of three 1-vectors in geometric algebra is instead the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_(mathematics)#Sign_of_a_direction"=
 title=3D"Sign (mathematics)">negative</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Vector_triple_product" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vecto=
r triple product">vector triple product</a> of the same three true vectors =
in vector algebra.
</p><p>Generalizations to higher dimensions is provided by the same commuta=
tor product of 2-vectors in higher-dimensional geometric algebras, but the =
2-vectors are no longer pseudovectors. Just as the commutator product/cross=
 product of 2-vectors in three dimensions <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Cross_product#Lie_algebra">correspond to the simplest Lie algebra</=
a>, the 2-vector subalgebras of higher dimensional geometric algebra equipp=
ed with the commutator product also correspond to the Lie algebras.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Cross_product#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Also as in three dimensions, the=
 commutator product could be further generalised to arbitrary multivectors.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multilinear_algebra">Multil=
inear algebra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DCross_product&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D36" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Multilinear algebra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilinear_a=
lgebra" title=3D"Multilinear algebra">multilinear algebra</a>, the cross pr=
oduct can be seen as the (1,2)-tensor (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mixed_tensor" title=3D"Mixed tensor">mixed tensor</a>, specifically =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_map" title=3D"Bilinear =
map">bilinear map</a>) obtained from the 3-dimensional <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume_form" title=3D"Volume form">volume form</a>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>not=
e 2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a (0,3)-tensor, by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raising_and_lowering_indices" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Raising and lowering indices">raising an index</a>.
</p><p>In detail, the 3-dimensional volume form defines a product <span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mat=
hml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"ht=
