<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCross_product&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1773, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph-Louis_Lagrange"=
 title=3D"Joseph-Louis Lagrange">Joseph-Louis Lagrange</a> used the compone=
nt form of both the dot and cross products in order to study the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron" title=3D"Tetrahedron">tetrahedr=
on</a> in three dimensions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-26"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>note 3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1843, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Rowan_Hami=
lton" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton">William Rowan Hamilton</a> introduce=
d the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion" title=3D"Quatern=
ion">quaternion</a> product, and with it the terms <i>vector</i> and <i>sca=
lar</i>. Given two quaternions <span class=3D"nowrap">[0, <b>u</b>]</span> =
and <span class=3D"nowrap">[0, <b>v</b>]</span>, where <b>u</b> and <b>v</b=
> are vectors in <b>R</b><sup>3</sup>, their quaternion product can be summ=
arized as <span class=3D"nowrap">[=E2=88=92<b>u</b> =E2=8B=85 <b>v</b>, <b>=
u</b> =C3=97 <b>v</b>]</span>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jam=
es_Clerk_Maxwell" title=3D"James Clerk Maxwell">James Clerk Maxwell</a> use=
d Hamilton's quaternion tools to develop his famous <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell%27s_equations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">elec=
tromagnetism equations</a>, and for this and other reasons quaternions for =
a time were an essential part of physics education.
</p><p>In 1844, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Grassmann"=
 title=3D"Hermann Grassmann">Hermann Grassmann</a> published a geometric al=
gebra not tied to dimension two or three. Grassmann developed several produ=
cts, including a cross product represented then by <span class=3D"texhtml">=
[uv]</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECajori1929[httpsarchiveorgdetailshi=
storyofmathema00cajo_0pages134_134]_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-FOOTNOTECajori1929[http=
sarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema00cajo_0pages134_134]-28"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (<i=
>See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exterior_algebra" title=
=3D"Exterior algebra">exterior algebra</a>.</i>)
</p><p>In 1853, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustin-Louis_Cau=
chy" title=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Augustin-Louis Cauchy</a>, a contempor=
ary of Grassmann, published a paper on algebraic keys which were used to so=
lve equations and had the same multiplication properties as the cross produ=
ct.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECrowe1994[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofvec=
tora0000crowpage83_83]_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-FOOTNOTECrowe1994[httpsarchiveorgdet=
ailshistoryofvectora0000crowpage83_83]-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_produ=
ct#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1878, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Kingdon_Cl=
ifford" title=3D"William Kingdon Clifford">William Kingdon Clifford</a>, kn=
own for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_algebra" title=
=3D"Geometric algebra">precursor</a> to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Clifford_algebra" title=3D"Clifford algebra">Clifford algebra</a>=
 named in his honor, published <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Elements_of_Dynamic" title=3D"Elements of Dynamic">Elements of Dynamic</a><=
/i>, in which the term <i>vector product</i> is attested. In the book, this=
 product of two vectors is defined to have magnitude equal to the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a> of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram"=
>parallelogram</a> of which they are two sides, and direction perpendicular=
 to their plane.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In lecture notes from 1881, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Josiah_Willard_Gibbs" title=3D"Josiah Willard Gibbs">Gibbs</a> represented=
 the cross product by <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inli=
ne"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"di=
splay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D=
"{\displaystyle u\times v}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>u</mi>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mi>v</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle u\times v}</a=
nnotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/dedbd3ae14284142498f3ff0777c08d2501df031" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:5.298ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle u\t=
imes v}"></span> and called it the <i>skew product</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_prod=
uct#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECrowe1994[httpsarc=
hiveorgdetailshistoryofvectora0000crowpage154_154]_33-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-FOOTNOTE=
Crowe1994[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofvectora0000crowpage154_154]-33"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> In 1901, Gibb's student <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Edwin_Bidwell_Wilson" title=3D"Edwin Bidwell Wilson">Edwin Bidwell Wilson</=
a> edited and extended these lecture notes into the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Textbook" title=3D"Textbook">textbook</a> <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_Analysis" title=3D"Vector Analysis">Vec=
tor Analysis</a></i>. Wilson kept the term <i>skew product</i>, but observe=
d that the alternative terms <i>cross product</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#ci=
te_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <i>vector product</i> were more frequent.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWilson1901[httpsarchiveorgdetails117714283page61_=
61]_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cros=
s_product#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWilson1901[httpsarchiveorgdetails117714283page6=
1_61]-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1908, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cesare_Burali-Fort=
i" title=3D"Cesare Burali-Forti">Cesare Burali-Forti</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roberto_Marcolongo" title=3D"Roberto Marcolongo"=
>Roberto Marcolongo</a> introduced the vector product notation <span class=
=3D"texhtml">u =E2=88=A7 v</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECajori1929[ht=
tpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema00cajo_0pages134_134]_28-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross_product#cite_note-F=
OOTNOTECajori1929[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema00cajo_0pages134_13=
4]-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> This is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/France" title=3D"France">France</a> and other areas until this day, as the=
 symbol <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \times }">
